    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1896-01-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1896-01-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="344" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d344">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Eustis</persName> to
                                    Mr. <persName type="to">Olney</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1896-01-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 24,
                                        1896</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Reply to your two telegrams, Clunet’s opinion is that a Frenchman can
                                sue the State, but not before ordinary judicial tribunals. Such
                                suits can only be brought before what are known here as
                                “administrative” tribunals. No difference in this respect between an
                                alien and a Frenchman.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Eustis</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
